`crates/steno/src` is the whole `steno` library crate: a one-way compiler pipeline from `.steno` theory source to Plover dictionaries and LSP/nvim snippet artifacts, plus the standalone binaries in `bin/` that actually write files to disk. Depending on this crate at the top level gets you the re-exports declared in `lib.rs`; nothing outside should reach into submodules directly.

The pipeline is strictly staged and one-directional: `parse/` (source text → `Entry`/`Chunk` AST) → `expand/` (counts, type-append, line-flag variants → `TypedEntry`) → `render/` and `snippet/` (typed entries → Plover dict entries / LSP snippet bodies). `stroke/` and `editor/` are cross-cutting engines consumed by multiple stages rather than pipeline stages themselves: `stroke/` supplies canonical stroke parsing/rendering and count-bank merging used wherever a construct's numeric arity must be folded into a key combination; `editor/` supplies the `Event` keystroke IR and `Behaviors` presets (`PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT`) that both `render/` and `blocks.rs` compile against to decide what a smart auto-indenting editor needs typed versus navigated. `json_out.rs` is the single serializer all dict/snippet builders funnel through to byte-for-byte match the original TS tool's `JSON.stringify` output — any escaping/ordering change there desyncs golden-file comparisons crate-wide. `error.rs` defines one error type per pipeline stage (all thin `String`-message wrappers implementing `Error`+`Display`); no stage panics on expected-failure input, everything funnels into these types, and `StenoError` is the only one carrying a structured field (`line()`).

The dominant cross-cutting coupling is profile semantics: `crate::editor::PLAIN`/`SMART` constants silently redefine output in both `render/` (auto-close-aware token dropping) and `blocks.rs` (navigation-vs-typed-text emission) with no code change required in those consumers — changing `Behaviors` fields ripples into both without a compiler error to catch it. A second crate-wide invariant: `terminal`-flag classification (set by `expand/family.rs`, consumed by both `render/` and `snippet/build.rs`) determines whether an entry is rendered as fully-typed text or left as a type-append intermediate; getting it wrong in either consumer corrupts output silently rather than failing loudly. All position/offset math throughout `editor/` is character-based, never byte-based.

`lib.rs` is the module map and re-export surface; `bin/` is the only place in the crate that performs file I/O, and it duplicates the parse→expand pipeline invocation per binary rather than sharing a driver.